{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"919158a6-9f36-477e-82c8-ed1c384eb82f","content":"Three distinct C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is now an error**\n\nC# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs (they synthesize methods incompatible with inline arrays). Fix: use a plain `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `Generator.cs` — `unsafe` context now flows into iterators**\n\nIn C# 12, `unsafe` on the class didn't propagate into iterator methods. C# 13 relaxed unsafe-in-iterators, so now the `unsafe` *does* flow in — making `yield return` sit inside an unsafe context, which is illegal.\n\nFix: remove `unsafe` from the class, scope it to the local function only:\n\n```csharp\nclass DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n        static unsafe void Process()\n        {\n            int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. `Resolver.cs` — New implicit span conversions cause ambiguity**\n\nC# 13 adds language-level implicit conversions between span types (`Span<T>` ↔ `ReadOnlySpan<T>`). This makes `Process([])` ambiguous — previously the compiler had a single best overload, now both are equally valid.\n\nFix: disambiguate with an explicit target type:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e7d59560-d3c6-4cf7-af4e-0ffe6966e279","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types. The fix is to change it to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in iterator methods via local functions: C# 13 tightened